          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">There=E2=80=99s a p=
alpable enthusiasm in political circles, <i>=C3=A0 la</i> 2016, ahead of to=
night=E2=80=99s historic presidential debate between <b>Joe Biden </b>and <=
b>Donald Trump</b>=E2=80=94the first time that a current and former Oval Of=
fice holder have engaged in televised battle about their competing visions =
for the nation. And given that this election season has coalesced around Tr=
ump=E2=80=99s legal headaches, the January 6 plot, Biden=E2=80=99s son=E2=
=80=99s own legal troubles, and questions about their advanced ages, tonigh=
t=E2=80=99s CNN debate promises to be <i>dramatic</i>, or at least less dep=
ressing than the rest of the cycle. <br/><br/>The debate, itself, is almost=
 certain to break viewership ratings for the network, particularly given it=
s various spellbinding cliffhangers: Will Trump interrupt Biden a zillion t=
imes, even with his mic turned off, or go apeshit over his recent
conviction? Will Biden have a senior moment? Will Trump? Will CNN=E2=80=99s=
 <b>Jake Tapper </b>and <b>Dana Bash</b> simply stand by while the former p=
resident uncorks one of his provably false bot mots? It=E2=80=99s the stuff=
 of great TV. Unfortunately, the future of democracy may hang on some of th=
ese points, too.  <br/><br/>I spent the past week polling my source base, b=
oth Democrats and Republicans, for their predictions, assessments, and expe=
ctations. Notably, a number of them suggested that each candidate could win=
 by <i>not losing</i>=E2=80=94a strategy perhaps best described as showing =
enough restraint to let the opposition self-immolate and thereby define the=
 choice in a voter=E2=80=99s mind. <br/>=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a 90-minute d=
ebate. If Donald Trump talked for 20 minutes, he would win the debate,=E2=
=80=9D one G.O.P. operative told me. =E2=80=9CTrump just can=E2=80=99t be a=
n asshole the way he was last time. If he can by some miracle do that, we=
=E2=80=99ll be looking good.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>A Democratic operative agre=
ed with
this cynical advice. =E2=80=9CBoth camps have this insane mentality that th=
ey will make the other side look terrible,=E2=80=9D this person told me. =
=E2=80=9CMost candidates in most campaigns walk in saying, <i>I want to be =
viewed as the best candidate and I want to look presidential on TV.</i> Now=
 it=E2=80=99s just, <i>I just need to make the other one look crazy or dumb=
</i>.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>One Democrat who advises the White House suggested=
 that Biden would win the debate if he simply impressed upon voters, one wa=
y or another, that he and Trump were the <i>only </i>candidates running=E2=
=80=94that neither <b>Gavin Newsom </b>nor <b>Michelle Obama </b>nor <b>Opr=
ah </b>or <b>The Rock </b>were going to descend from the heavens at the las=
t minute. Indeed, on some level, this comports with the White House=E2=80=
=99s overarching strategy of portraying this election as not simply a refer=
endum on Biden, but on his opponent as well=E2=80=94a sticky wicket for a s=
itting president, but one that has been made more achievable given
Trump=E2=80=99s repeated comments about running the government like a dicta=
torship (at least on Day One). =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m sure Biden will be fine=
, like the State of the Union. As long as he=E2=80=99s cogent and speaks we=
ll, he=E2=80=99ll pass his test,=E2=80=9D a G.O.P. operative said. =E2=80=
=9CAs for Trump, he has to be smart, a little charming, responsible, and if=
 he can, act like a grown-up.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>But if Biden does nothing d=
uring CNN=E2=80=99s 90-minute showdown other than debunk the misapprehensio=
n among 17 percent of independents and even 12 percent of Democrats that <i=
